<ArticleLayout
  title="Zone 2: What It Is, Why It Matters, and How to Find Yours"
  description="The foundational explainer. What zone 2 training actually is, what the research shows it does, and how to find your personal zone 2 intensity."
  type="article"
>

<div class="key-takeaway">
  <p><strong>Zone 2 is steady, moderate-intensity exercise that trains your mitochondria to burn fat and clear lactate more efficiently.</strong> It's the intensity at which you can hold a conversation but not sing. Research shows it improves cardiovascular health, metabolic flexibility, and may be the most important type of exercise for long-term health. Most people aren't doing enough of it — and the ones who exercise regularly are often going too hard.</p>
</div>

<h2>What "zone 2" actually means</h2>

<p>Heart rate training zones divide your effort into bands, from rest to all-out. Different systems use different numbers of zones — three, five, even seven — which is why "zone 2" can mean slightly different things depending on who you're listening to.</p>

<p>When researchers and practitioners like Iñigo San Millán talk about zone 2, they mean something specific: <strong>the highest intensity at which your body can sustain exercise primarily through fat oxidation, with lactate production staying low and stable.</strong> In a five-zone model, this corresponds to roughly 60-70% of your heart rate reserve (the gap between your resting and maximum heart rate).</p>

<p class="citation">San-Millán, I. & Brooks, G.A. (2018). "Assessment of Metabolic Flexibility by Means of Measuring Blood Lactate, Fat, and Carbohydrate Oxidation Responses to Exercise." Sports Medicine, 48(Suppl 1), 91-104.</p>

<p>At this intensity, several things happen simultaneously:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Your slow-twitch muscle fibres are doing most of the work, burning fat as their primary fuel</li>
  <li>Your fast-twitch fibres contribute a small, steady trickle of lactate</li>
  <li>Your slow-twitch fibres are clearing that lactate — using it as fuel — roughly as fast as it's produced</li>
  <li>Your breathing is elevated but controlled. You can talk in complete sentences</li>
</ul>

<p>This is a sustainable intensity. You could maintain it for an hour or more without accumulating fatigue. It doesn't feel heroic. It feels... moderate. And that modesty is exactly what makes it effective.</p>

<h2>Why it matters for your health</h2>

<h3>Mitochondrial function</h3>

<p>Mitochondria are the structures inside your cells that produce energy. Their density and efficiency directly affect how well your body burns fat, manages blood sugar, and sustains physical effort. San Millán's research, developed over thousands of metabolic tests with athletes and patients, found that zone 2 is the intensity that stimulates mitochondrial adaptation most effectively.</p>

<p class="citation">San-Millán, I. (2023). "The Key Role of Mitochondrial Function in Health and Disease." Antioxidants, 12(4), 782.</p>

<p>As we age, mitochondrial function naturally declines. Sedentary lifestyles accelerate this decline. Mitochondrial dysfunction is linked to type 2 diabetes, cardiovascular disease, and neurodegenerative conditions. Currently, no medication reliably increases mitochondrial function. Exercise — particularly sustained moderate-intensity exercise — is the most effective intervention we have.</p>

<h3>Fat metabolism</h3>

<p>Zone 2 is where your body burns the highest proportion of fat relative to carbohydrate. This isn't just relevant for weight management — it's a marker of metabolic flexibility, your body's ability to switch between fuel sources depending on demand. Poor metabolic flexibility is an early indicator of insulin resistance and metabolic syndrome.</p>

<p>Training in zone 2 improves your capacity to oxidise fat at rest and during exercise. Over weeks and months, this shifts your metabolic profile: you become better at using fat for everyday energy, you preserve glycogen for when you actually need it, and your blood sugar regulation improves.</p>

<h3>Cardiovascular health</h3>

<p>Zone 2 training increases stroke volume — the amount of blood your heart pumps per beat. Over time, your heart becomes more efficient: lower resting heart rate, lower heart rate at any given effort level, and better blood pressure regulation. This is the "aerobic base" that endurance athletes talk about, but it's equally important for people who will never run a race.</p>

<h3>Lactate clearance</h3>

<p>Lactate isn't waste — it's fuel. But if your body produces lactate faster than it can clear it (during intense exercise), it accumulates and contributes to fatigue. Zone 2 training specifically trains your slow-twitch muscle fibres to absorb and use lactate, improving your clearance capacity. This makes higher-intensity exercise feel easier, even though you're not training at high intensity.</p>

<p class="citation">Brooks, G.A. (2020). "Lactate as a fulcrum of metabolism." Redox Biology, 35, 101454.</p>

<h2>Why most people get it wrong</h2>

<p>The most common mistake is going too hard. Research on polarised training — the approach used by most elite endurance athletes — shows that roughly 80% of training time should be at zone 2 or below, with only 20% at high intensity. Most recreational exercisers have this ratio inverted.</p>

<p class="citation">Seiler, S. (2010). "What is best practice for training intensity and duration distribution in endurance athletes?" International Journal of Sports Physiology and Performance, 5(3), 276-291.</p>

<p>This happens because zone 2 feels "too easy." People assume that if they're not breathing hard, sweating heavily, or feeling exhausted, the workout isn't doing anything. In reality, the physiological adaptations from zone 2 are profound — they're just not dramatic in the moment.</p>

<p>For many people, especially those who are heavier or less aerobically fit, even slow jogging pushes heart rate well above zone 2. This is one of the reasons loaded walking is so effective as a zone 2 modality: you can walk at a comfortable pace, add weight to bring your heart rate into zone 2, and maintain that intensity for the full session without the joint impact or ego challenges of shuffling along at a very slow jog.</p>

<h2>How much zone 2 do you need?</h2>

<p>San Millán recommends three to four sessions per week for the first two to three months, with each session lasting 45-60 minutes. After that initial adaptation period, this can be reduced to two to three sessions per week for maintenance.</p>

<p>Peter Attia, who popularised zone 2 training through his book <em>Outlive</em> and his podcast <em>The Drive</em>, aims for four zone 2 sessions per week of approximately 45-60 minutes each — roughly three to four hours of total zone 2 time per week. He describes this as the "minimum effective dose" for meaningful metabolic improvement.</p>

<p>If that sounds like a lot, the good news is that even smaller amounts are beneficial. A 2025 narrative review in <em>Sports Medicine</em> found that for people training fewer than six hours per week, combining zone 2 with some higher-intensity work produced better outcomes than zone 2 alone.</p>

<p class="citation">Biddle, S. et al. (2025). "Zone 2 Training for Health and Longevity: A Narrative Review." Sports Medicine (published online July 2025).</p>

<p>In practical terms: two or three sessions of 30-45 minutes per week is a meaningful starting point. You don't need to hit four hours immediately. Consistency over weeks and months matters more than any single session.</p>

<h2>How to find your zone 2</h2>

<p>There are three practical approaches, in order of accuracy:</p>

<h3>1. The Karvonen method (best without lab testing)</h3>

<p>This uses your heart rate reserve — the difference between your maximum and resting heart rate — to calculate personalised zones. Zone 2 falls at 60-70% of your heart rate reserve, plus your resting heart rate.</p>

<p>You need two numbers: your resting heart rate (measure first thing in the morning, average over 3-5 days) and your maximum heart rate (from a test, or estimated by formula).</p>

<p>The standard 220-minus-age formula for max heart rate has a standard deviation of ±10-12 bpm, which is significant for zone 2 accuracy. The Tanaka formula (208 − 0.7 × age) is more accurate across age ranges. For women, the Gulati formula (206 − 0.88 × age) is better still.</p>

<p class="citation">Tanaka, H. et al. (2001). "Age-predicted maximal heart rate revisited." Journal of the American College of Cardiology, 37(1), 153-156.</p>

<p>Use our <a href={`${base}/find-your-zone`}>zone 2 calculator</a> to do this automatically.</p>

<h3>2. The talk test (no equipment needed)</h3>

<p>Speak out loud while exercising. If you can talk in full sentences but couldn't comfortably sing, you're in zone 2. This has been validated by research as a reliable proxy for the ventilatory threshold that marks the top of zone 2.</p>

<p>Read the full <a href={`${base}/guides/talk-test`}>talk test guide</a>.</p>

<h3>3. Lab metabolic testing (gold standard)</h3>

<p>A graded exercise test with blood lactate sampling or gas exchange analysis is the most accurate way to determine your personal zone 2. San Millán defines the top of zone 2 as the intensity where blood lactate first shows a sustained rise above baseline — typically around 2 mmol/L. This test is available at sports science labs and some specialist gyms, typically costing £100-200.</p>

<p>For most people, the Karvonen method combined with the talk test provides sufficient accuracy. Lab testing is valuable if you're training seriously or want to track your metabolic improvement over time.</p>

<h2>Zone 2 and loaded walking</h2>

<p>Zone 2 can be achieved through any sustained, rhythmic exercise: cycling, rowing, swimming, jogging, or walking. The reason loaded walking works so well is that it solves the two most common problems people face with zone 2:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Walking alone isn't enough.</strong> For moderately fit people, unloaded walking at any pace may not raise heart rate into zone 2. Adding weight bridges that gap without needing to jog.</li>
  <li><strong>Jogging is often too much.</strong> Many people — especially those carrying extra body weight — find that even slow jogging pushes heart rate above zone 2. They have no "zone 2 pace" available while running. Walking with a load gives them one.</li>
</ul>

<p>Adding a weighted pack or vest turns walking into a legitimate zone 2 training modality. It's accessible, low-impact, requires no gym, works outdoors, and can be adjusted precisely by changing the weight or pace.</p>

